nd experimental advances have demonstrated that molecular structure alone does not control SOM stability: in fact, environmental and biological controls predominate. Here we propose ways to include this understanding in a new generation of experiments and soil carbon models, thereby improving predictions of the SOM response to global warming. © 2011 Macmillan Publishers Limited. All rights reserved.",,"carbon; soil organic matter; biological control; climate change; ecosystem resilience; global warming; persistence; soil organic matter; terrestrial ecosystem; atmosphere; chemical structure; decomposition; ecosystem; greenhouse effect; prediction; priority journal; review; soil; vegetation; Bioengineering; Carbon; Carbon Cycle; Charcoal; Climate Change; Ecosystem; Freezing; Organic Chemicals; Plant Roots; Plants; Soil; Soil Microbiology",,"carbon, 7440-44-0; Carbon, 7440-44-0; Charcoal, 16291-96-6; Organic Chemicals; Soil; biochar",,,,"Fischlin, A., (2007) Climate Change 2007: Impacts, Adaptation and Vulnerability, pp. 211-272. , (eds Parry, M. L., Canziani, O. F., Palutikof, J. P., van der Linden, P. J. & Hanson, C. E.) Cambridge Univ. Press; Friedlingstein, P., Cox, P., Betts, R., Bopp, L., Von Bloh, W., Brovkin, V., Cadule, P., Zeng, N., Climate-carbon cycle feedback analysis: Results from the C 4MIP model intercomparison (2006) Journal of Climate, 19 (14), pp. 3337-3353. , DOI 10.1175/JCLI3800.1; Von Lützow, M., Köel-Knabner, I., Temperature sensitivity of soil organic matter decomposition-what do we know? (2009) Biol. Fertil. Soils, 46, pp. 1-15; Kirschbaum, M.U.F., The temperature dependence of organic-matter decomposition - Still a topic of debate (2006) Soil Biology and Biochemistry, 38 (9), pp. 2510-2518. , DOI 10.1016/j.soilbio.2006.01.030; Heimann, M., Reichstein, M., Terrestrial ecosystemcarbon dynamics and climate feedbacks (2008) Nature, 451, pp. 289-292; Trumbore, S.E., Czimczik, C.I., An uncertain future for soil carbon (2008) Science, 321, pp. 1455-1